{
  "doc_id": "50472",
  "text": "Midline 1 (MID1) is the gene responsible for Opitz G/BBB syndrome (OS), which is characterized by malformations that affect midline structures, such as laryngotracheoesophageal, cardiac and urogenital abnormalities. Mid1 is a microtubule-associated E3 ubiquitin ligase [CITATION_1] that regulates the degradation of the catalytic subunit of protein phosphatase 2A (Ppp2ca) via interaction with the α4 subunit of Pp2a [CITATION_2] . One-third of individuals with OS also exhibit developmental defects of the CNS, which mainly consist of hypoplasia/agenesis of the medial cerebellum [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] ; however, clinical manifestations of OS in the CNS, as well as in the body, show variable expressivity. Indeed, although Mid1-KO mice have been reported to show hypoplasia of the anterior portion of the medial cerebellum, no other abnormalities were observed [CITATION_5] . Furthermore, no correlation between the position of the mutation in MID1 and clinical phenotypes of OS has been reported [CITATION_6] . Thus, the underlying pathogenesis of OS remains to be fully elucidated.",
